  "prompt": "What are some good science fiction novels to read next?",
  "response": "There are countless excellent science fiction novels to explore, depending on your preferences. Here\u2019s a curated list of classics and modern favorites to consider:\n\n### **Classic Science Fiction**\n1. **Dune** by Frank Herbert  \n   A sweeping epic of politics, religion, and ecology on a desert planet.\n\n2. **Neuromancer** by William Gibson  \n   The seminal cyberpunk novel that redefined the genre.\n\n3. **Foundation** by Isaac Asimov  \n   A grand saga about the rise and fall of galactic empires.\n\n4. **1984** by George Orwell  \n   A dystopian masterpiece exploring surveillance and totalitarianism.\n\n5. **The Left Hand of Darkness** by Ursula K. Le Guin  \n   A profound exploration of gender and society on an alien world.\n\n6. **Snow Crash** by Neal Stephenson  \n   A fast-paced, satirical cyberpunk adventure.\n\n### **Modern Science Fiction**\n7. **The Three-Body Problem** by Liu Cixin  \n   A mind-bending hard sci-fi novel with cosmic stakes.\n\n8. **The Martian** by Andy Weir  \n   A gripping survival story set on Mars, blending science and humor.\n\n9. **Annihilation** by Jeff VanderMeer  \n   A surreal and eerie tale of exploration in a mysterious zone.\n\n10. **Exhalation** by Ted Chiang  \n    A collection of thought-provoking and beautifully written short stories.\n\n11. **Children of Time** by Adrian Tchaikovsky  \n    An ambitious story of evolution, AI, and interstellar conflict.\n\n12. **A Memory Called Empire** by Arkady Martine  \n    A political intrigue-filled space opera with rich world-building.\n\n### **Mind-Bending and Philosophical**\n13. **Blindsight** by Peter Watts  \n    A dark, hard sci-fi exploration of consciousness and alien intelligence.\n\n14. **Hyperion** by Dan Simmons  \n    A poetic and epic tale of pilgrims traveling to a mysterious world.\n\n15. **Ubik** by Philip K. Dick  \n    A surreal and mind-bending exploration of reality and identity.\n\n### **Space Opera and Adventure**\n16. **Leviathan Wakes** by James S.A. Corey  \n    The first book in *The Expanse* series, a thrilling space opera.\n\n17. **Old Man's War** by John Scalzi  \n    A fun and action-packed story of aging soldiers in space.\n\n18. **The Long Way to a Small, Angry Planet** by Becky Chambers  \n    A heartwarming and character-driven space adventure.\n\n### **Dystopian and Speculative**\n19. **Brave New World** by Aldous Huxley  \n    A classic dystopian novel exploring societal control and freedom.\n\n20. **Station Eleven** by Emily St. John Mandel  \n    A post-apocalyptic story about art, memory, and humanity.\n\n### **Experimental and Unique**\n21. **Borne** by Jeff VanderMeer  \n    A strange and haunting story of biotech and survival in a ruined world.\n\n22. **The City & the City** by China Mi\u00e9ville  \n    A blend of crime fiction and speculative ideas about parallel cities.\n\nLet me know if you\u2019d like more recommendations or details about any of these!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
